scripts/ is the Layer 1 quality-gate suite: static/format/lint/dependency checks that CI and the pre-commit hook run against the Rust workspace, plus one unrelated maintenance script for syncing external tooling. Depending on this directory means invoking `ci.sh` (optionally with a root-dir argument) and treating its aggregate exit code as the sole pass/fail signal; individual scripts are also independently invocable with the same `[root_dir=.]` convention.

`ci.sh` is the authoritative list of what "Layer 1" means — its `RUN` sequence is the only place a check gets added, removed, or reordered. It runs `cargo fmt`, `cargo clippy`, `cargo doc`, `cargo deny`, `cargo machete`, then four repo-local scripts in this directory: `rationale_check.py`, `workspace_lints_check.sh`, `no_allow_check.sh`, `cycle_check.sh`. It never short-circuits (no `-e`), so all checks always run and all failures are reported together.

Three of the four repo-local scripts (`rationale_check.py`, `no_allow_check.sh`, `workspace_lints_check.sh`) share a load-bearing enumeration pattern: `git ls-files -z --cached --others --exclude-standard` instead of a filesystem walk, specifically to avoid racing `target/` writes from a concurrent cargo build and to keep results a pure function of tracked/untracked-but-not-ignored repo state. Any new Layer 1 script that scans the tree should follow this same pattern rather than `rglob`/`find`. `no_allow_check.sh`'s grep output format (`path:line:` prefix, forced via a `/dev/null` sentinel arg) is a cross-repo contract with `ctx-verify`'s output parser elsewhere in the codebase — changing that format breaks a different tool silently.

`cycle_check.sh` is currently a stub: it only checks that `cargo-modules` runs, and does not detect cycles despite its name and purpose — real detection is deferred to a future dylint rule documented in `docs/DYLINT_RULES.md`. `rationale_check.py`'s brace-balance/regex heuristics are similarly an acknowledged MVP standing in for that same future dylint pipeline, as is the module-cycle stub — both are expected to be superseded together. `workspace_lints_check.sh` is explicitly *not* slated for dylint replacement, since it's a manifest-level property rather than a source-level lint.

`install-tools.sh` is unrelated to the Layer 1 checks: it's the one-way sync mechanism that builds and installs the `ctx-*` tool binaries and summarizer prompts from a sibling CTX tooling repo into this project, and must be rerun manually whenever that repo changes or after copying `template/`.